41
00:02:26.840 --> 00:02:29.560
Since the fall of France.
the BBC has broadcast

42
00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:32.520
daily radio programming
to occupied Europe.

43
00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:37.040
Embedded within the broadcasts
are coded messages.

44
00:02:41.560 --> 00:02:44.520
The night before D-Day.
the Allied invasion

45
00:02:44.680 --> 00:02:45.960
of Western Europe.

46
00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:47.920
the broadcast to occupied France

47
00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:50.800
includes a line from a poem
by Paul Verlaine.

48
00:02:57.880 --> 00:02:59.920
The French resistance is waiting.

49
00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:01.920
and when the BBC announces:

50
00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:03.960
"Wound my heart with
a monotonous languor."

51
00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:06.400
this is the word that they
have been waiting to hear:

52
00:03:06.560 --> 00:03:08.680
the invasion is on.

53
00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:13.560
The Allies want that
resistance movement to rise up.

54
00:03:13.720 --> 00:03:15.520
to blow up German railroads. to

55
00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:18.520
ambush German patrols.
and to disrupt the Germans

56
00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:20.200
in any way they can.

57
00:03:21.480 --> 00:03:22.920
All of their planning.

58
00:03:23.080 --> 00:03:24.840
all of their networking
now goes into action

59
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:27.360
to slow the German response

60
00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:28.960
so that the Allies
can win the race

61
00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:30.840
to build up and break out.

62
00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.320
So many men and women
throughout France

63
00:03:33.480 --> 00:03:37.160
have risked so
much to get to this night

64
00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:40.200
and the beginning of
their country's liberation.

65
00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:44.600
After the
fall of France in 1940.

66
00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:45.840
there are two Frances.

67
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.280
There's the France
that is directly occupied by

68
00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:49.960
the Germans. including Paris.

69
00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:53.720
and there is a puppet regime
with its capital at Vichy.

70
00:03:53.880 --> 00:03:56.920
So resistance
groups form in each one.

71
00:03:58.840 --> 00:04:02.080
From the start. the
inspiration for French resistance

72
00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:05.120
to Germany
was embodied by one man.

73
00:04:07.480 --> 00:04:09.720
A veteran of the Great War.

74
00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:11.880
General Charles De Gaulle.

75
00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:13.600
Charles De Gaulle

76
00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:15.840
fought all the way
through the German invasion

77
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:17.920
of France in 1940.

78
00:04:18.080 --> 00:04:19.760
Rather than
surrender to the Germans.

79
00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:21.640
rather than go along
with the French government.

80
00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:23.200
he arrives in Britain by himself

81
00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:24.400
and just says. "By the way.

82
00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:26.040
I'm now
the leader of the Free French."

83
00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:27.480
He's self-appointed.

84
00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:30.360
Churchill goes.
"Eh. he might be useful."

85
00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:32.440
He gives him an office.
gives him a radio.

86
00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:33.840
lets him do some broadcasts.

87
00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:42.560
He's gonna announce:

88
00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:44.400
"The Vichy
government is illegitimate."

89
00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:46.560
Anybody who's in France
should come over to England.

90
00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:48.280
and we're gonna start
to put together an army

91
00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:49.800
that's gonna liberate ourselves.

92
00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:51.320
If you can't get here.
you should start

93
00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:52.760
resisting while you're there."

94
00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:56.320
This is an
extremely important event

95
00:04:56.480 --> 00:04:58.200
in galvanizing
the French people.

96
00:04:58.360 --> 00:05:01.160
Up to that point. they'd been
in a state of despondency

97
00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:04.120
at the rapid defeat at
the hands of the Germans.

98
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:06.200
Now. here was a voice.

99
00:05:06.360 --> 00:05:09.640
one of their own.
offering them hope.

100
00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:12.440
He says.
"The flame of French resistance

101
00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:16.480
Must not be extinguished.
and will not be extinguished."

102
00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:19.200
These are words
that French men and women

103
00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:20.600
were longing to hear.

104
00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:23.440
It's not only the beginning
of the resistance.

105
00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:26.040
it's the beginning of the rise
of Charles De Gaulle

106
00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:28.000
to political power in France.

107
00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:32.920
Resistance pops
up all over the country.

108
00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:35.280
But these groups aren't connected.

109
00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:37.080
and they all stand
for different things.

110
00:05:38.240 --> 00:05:40.200
There are
aristocratic Catholics.

111
00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:42.440
Communists. Republicans.

112
00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:45.000
There are all different
groups jockeying for position

113
00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:46.960
between themselves
and fighting against

114
00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:48.200
the Germans as well.

115
00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:51.640
A cross-section
of French citizens.

116
00:05:51.800 --> 00:05:55.360
teachers. lawyers.
farmers. factory workers.

117
00:05:55.520 --> 00:05:57.240
take part in the resistance.

118
00:05:59.080 --> 00:06:01.360
Women play a substantial role.

119
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.760
One of the
most important activities

120
00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:08.920
of the resistance was
a network of agents

121
00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:10.920
and secret codes
and safe houses

122
00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:14.880
that helped smuggle downed
Allied flyers out of France

123
00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:17.440
and back to safety in Britain.

124
00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:21.880
This underground railroad helped
about 5.000 Allied flyers

125
00:06:22.040 --> 00:06:24.360
make it to freedom
in the course of the war.

126
00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:28.760
It's the
potential of the Allied invasion

127
00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:32.000
eventually reaching
France that cause volunteers

128
00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:33.880
to flock to the resistance.

129
00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:39.360
They're gathering equipment.
supplies. weapons

130
00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:41.800
because they think:
"Eventually. we will be freed.

131
00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:43.600
How do we help accelerate that?"

132
00:06:48.640 --> 00:06:50.240
The night before D-Day.

133
00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:53.280
dozens of Allied agents are
dropped behind German lines

134
00:06:53.440 --> 00:06:56.520
to coordinate with groups
of the French resistance.

135
00:06:56.680 --> 00:06:59.480
so-called "Jedburgh teams."

136
00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:02.720
Three-man teams

137
00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:04.480
who parachute into occupied

138
00:07:04.640 --> 00:07:07.960
an American. a British.
and a French agent.

139
00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:10.880
They
bring weapons with them.

140
00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:12.840
They'd bring a radio set
so they could communicate.

141
00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:16.080
They coordinate activities.

142
00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:19.360
and they inform the groups
what the Allies are up to.

143
00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:23.440
The Jedburghs have an ultimate
goal. and that is to

144
00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:27.600
ease the invasion plan
for June. 1944.

145
00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:34.080
Once the Allies
land in June 6th.

146
00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:36.360
the resistance
becomes emboldened.

147
00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:41.120
But many pay a grievous
price for their courage.

148
00:07:41.280 --> 00:07:43.560
Germans. with the help
of French collaborators.

149
00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:47.280
hunt down anyone
assisting the Allies.

150
00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:49.160
The costs
of being in the resistance

151
00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:51.600
or around the resistance
are incredibly high.

152
00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:53.480
They could be
arrested and put in jail.

153
00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:55.640
they could be sent to
a labor camp. hung.

154
00:07:55.800 --> 00:07:58.120
oftentimes without trial
and in public

155
00:07:58.280 --> 00:07:59.960
as a deterrence
to everyone else.

156
00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:03.880
The Gestapo
carryout reprisals.

157
00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:06.000
"For every one of
our soldiers killed.

158
00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:08.160
we will kill 50
resistance fighters."

159
00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:13.760
Four days after the invasion.

160
00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:16.480
near the village of
Oradour-sur-Glane.

161
00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:20.440
the local resistance kills
an SS battalion commander.

162
00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:24.400
Nazi retribution is
swift and merciless.

163
00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:27.200
They take all the men and they

164
00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:28.720
shove them into
a bunch of barns.

165
00:08:28.880 --> 00:08:30.320
shoot them.
and set the barns on fire.

166
00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:33.040
They take all the
women and children

167
00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:34.560
and put them in a church

168
00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:36.880
and then burn the church
to the ground.

169
00:08:37.040 --> 00:08:39.680
shooting anyone
who tries to climb out.

170
00:08:40.600 --> 00:08:44.160
Collective vengeance
for the act of resistance.

171
00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:50.000
On July 25th.
the Americans launch

172
00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:52.000
a massive air and ground attack:

173
00:08:52.160 --> 00:08:54.000
Operation Cobra.

174
00:08:55.840 --> 00:08:58.120
After a month
and a half of combat

175
00:08:58.280 --> 00:09:00.040
among the hedgerows
of Normandy.

176
00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:02.600
the Allies now break through

177
00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:04.760
the German defensive perimeter.

178
00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:10.000
Paris is the center
of the German occupying force.

179
00:09:10.160 --> 00:09:13.160
But the Allies were not
super interested in Paris.

180
00:09:14.120 --> 00:09:16.720
Cities are an enormous
military problem.

181
00:09:16.880 --> 00:09:18.920
Do you go into Paris
knowing that you could

182
00:09:19.080 --> 00:09:22.080
end up fighting an urban battle
that you don't want to fight?

183
00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:24.120
The streets narrow
your ability to maneuver.

184
00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:26.720
So fighting inside a city
is nobody's idea

185
00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:28.440
of what you want to do.

186
00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:31.440
Of course. if you're French. the
situation is completely different.

187
00:09:32.480 --> 00:09:35.760
The French people are
thinking that the Allies are

188
00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:38.800
just a few hundred
kilometers from the city of Paris.

189
00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:41.640
and they believe
that Paris will be next

190
00:09:41.800 --> 00:09:44.640
in the great capitals of
Europe to be liberated

191
00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:46.880
from Nazi fascism.

192
00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:50.000
To the French. Paris
is not just the capital of France.

193
00:09:50.160 --> 00:09:52.720
It is the most important.
most symbolic city

194
00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:54.320
that you're going to liberate.

195
00:09:54.480 --> 00:09:56.880
And the man who thinks
he's going to take control

196
00:09:57.040 --> 00:09:58.720
of all of this is
Charles De Gaulle.

197
00:10:01.360 --> 00:10:02.640
Throughout the war.

198
00:10:02.800 --> 00:10:06.040
he builds up Free French
forces in London and in Africa.

199
00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:08.880
French soldiers
flock to his colors.

200
00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.280
And. by D-Day.
he has something of

201
00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:14.200
a Free French armed force.

202
00:10:14.360 --> 00:10:18.000
And De Gaulle is astonished
and appalled

203
00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:20.640
to hear that the Allies are not

204
00:10:20.800 --> 00:10:23.200
focusing on Paris
as a key objective.

205
00:10:23.360 --> 00:10:27.400
Paris is like the beating
heart of the French republic.

206
00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:29.200
There is no France
without Paris.

207
00:10:30.040 --> 00:10:33.440
And De Gaulle said.
"If you're not going. I'm going."

208
00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:47.680
Allied forces
advance across France

209
00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:50.800
to force the Wehrmacht's retreat
to the Rhine and beyond.

210
00:10:53.440 --> 00:10:55.920
Liberating Paris
from German occupation

211
00:10:56.080 --> 00:10:58.280
is not their main
strategic concern.

212
00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:01.800
But Parisians have other ideas.

213
00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:03.360
The problem
for Paris is that.

214
00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:04.840
when the Normandy invasion
happens.

215
00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.840
it cuts the city off from
its principal food supply.

216
00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.000
And the Germans are
trying to take everything

217
00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:11.480
that they can out of the city.

218
00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:14.920
So it's a very. very unstable.
very insecure place.

219
00:11:16.120 --> 00:11:17.680
And so there is the beginnings

220
00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:19.720
of popular uprising in Paris.

221
00:11:19.880 --> 00:11:22.840
A lot of that is being driven
by the communist resistance.

222
00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:24.640
De Gaulle is quite
keen to get to Paris.

223
00:11:24.800 --> 00:11:27.560
because what he doesn't
is Paris to

224
00:11:27.720 --> 00:11:30.160
become liberated by
the communist resistance.

225
00:11:30.320 --> 00:11:32.600
He does not want
to liberate France

226
00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:35.320
only for it to fall into
the hands of communism.

227
00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:40.480
To ensure that
French troops liberate Paris.

228
00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:42.520
General De Gaulle
requires the support

229
00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:44.480
of the Supreme
Allied Commander:

230
00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:46.960
General Dwight Eisenhower.

231
00:11:47.120 --> 00:11:49.120
De Gaulle
didn't have that many cards

232
00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:50.960
to play in 1944.

233
00:11:51.120 --> 00:11:53.520
but he played them
as skillfully as anybody.

234
00:11:53.680 --> 00:11:55.960
There is a French unit.
the Second Armored Division.

235
00:11:56.120 --> 00:11:57.760
controlled by General
Philippe Leclerc. that

236
00:11:57.920 --> 00:11:59.960
has been disobeying American
orders to get closer

237
00:12:00.120 --> 00:12:01.840
and closer and closer to
the city so that it could

238
00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.280
go into Paris if it had to.

239
00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:07.760
And so De Gaulle
became very aggressive about

240
00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:10.240
steering the Second
Armored Division toward the city.

241
00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:12.560
He gave General
Leclerc specific

242
00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:15.000
instructions to. "No matter what
these Americans tell you.

243
00:12:15.160 --> 00:12:16.680
I need you to get to Paris."

244
00:12:17.840 --> 00:12:19.440
As Winston
Churchill would say.

245
00:12:19.600 --> 00:12:21.440
he tends to love to bite
the hand that feeds him.

246
00:12:21.600 --> 00:12:23.040
You have to give
him credit. though.

247
00:12:23.200 --> 00:12:24.720
for he has his eye on one thing.

248
00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:26.000
and that's a free France.

249
00:12:33.160 --> 00:12:35.720
Shortly after D-Day.
in coordination with

250
00:12:35.880 --> 00:12:38.360
their Western allies.
the Soviets throw

251
00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:41.360
the massed might of the Red
Army against the Germans.

252
00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:44.280
Operation Bagration is

253
00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:46.000
the gigantic Soviet offensive

254
00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:47.720
in summer of 1944.

255
00:12:47.880 --> 00:12:49.160
Roughly timed to coincide

256
00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:51.360
with the Allies
landing in Normandy.

257
00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:55.400
It is just
a monstrous offensive.

258
00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:57.520
About two and a half million

259
00:12:57.680 --> 00:12:59.160
Soviets are thrown into battle.

260
00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:02.720
Half a million Germans are killed.
wounded. or captured.

261
00:13:04.360 --> 00:13:07.840
It erased an entire
German army group from the map.

262
00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.880
the entire central portion of
the German front in the east.

263
00:13:14.960 --> 00:13:17.720
Now the Soviet army
is moving in to Poland.

264
00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:19.960
and you've gotta remember that.
of course.

265
00:13:20.120 --> 00:13:22.440
Poland was the reason
the war started.

266
00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:27.840
In the fall of 1939.
Adolf Hitler and Joseph Stalin

267
00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:29.880
agreed to divide Poland.

268
00:13:31.040 --> 00:13:32.760
When Hitler took Poland.

269
00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:37.840
he treated it like the laboratory
for his racial ideas.

270
00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.520
his plans to annihilate
the Jewish people

271
00:13:41.680 --> 00:13:46.200
and to treat the
Eastern Slavic people

272
00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:50.120
as essentially a slave
race to work to death.

273
00:13:52.240 --> 00:13:55.800
Poland has been
stained in blood and killing.

274
00:13:55.960 --> 00:13:58.320
crushed beneath
the German jackboot.

275
00:13:58.480 --> 00:14:00.960
its soil watered with the blood of

276
00:14:01.120 --> 00:14:03.120
vast numbers of its
Jewish community.

277
00:14:05.160 --> 00:14:09.160
The Poles have been
living through hell for five years.

278
00:14:09.320 --> 00:14:11.960
If you're a resident of Warsaw.
you are one of the most

279
00:14:12.120 --> 00:14:13.880
unlucky people
ever to have lived.

280
00:14:17.480 --> 00:14:19.800
Throughout this
horror show that has been

281
00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:22.120
inflicted upon the Poles.
they have maintained

282
00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:25.480
a shadow government.
a kind of national cohesion.

283
00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:27.240
They have a government-in-exile
in London.

284
00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:30.040
and it is sending orders
to a home army.

285
00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:32.000
a sort of
secret army of underground

286
00:14:32.160 --> 00:14:34.400
resistance fighters in Poland.

287
00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:39.200
The Polish Home Army
was formed really

288
00:14:39.360 --> 00:14:41.520
immediately after
the Germans invaded.

289
00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:42.760
There was a real sense.

290
00:14:42.920 --> 00:14:44.560
in amongst the Polish community.

291
00:14:44.720 --> 00:14:46.880
and especially the young
people: "We're gonna fight."

292
00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:50.320
It was always set up as a
formal military organization.

293
00:14:50.480 --> 00:14:52.440
It wasn't just an ad hoc
bunch of partisans.

294
00:14:53.400 --> 00:14:55.920
They undertook intelligence
gatherings of troop movements.

295
00:14:56.080 --> 00:14:58.280
They gathered
information about the camps.

296
00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:00.360
about Auschwitz. and others.

297
00:15:01.720 --> 00:15:04.840
The Home Army is
led by a former cavalry officer

298
00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.680
who has been fighting
the Germans since 1939...

299
00:15:10.120 --> 00:15:12.640
General Tadeusz Bór-Komorowski.

300
00:15:16.840 --> 00:15:19.280
On July 29th. 1944.

301
00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:21.520
as the Allies are
slicing through France.

302
00:15:21.680 --> 00:15:25.120
the Soviets reach
the outskirts of Warsaw.

303
00:15:28.200 --> 00:15:30.120
The Polish Home Army
is waiting for the moment

304
00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:31.920
when the Germans
are about to retreat

305
00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:34.880
and just before
the Soviets arrive.

306
00:15:35.040 --> 00:15:36.720
Because that is the opportunity

307
00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:40.600
to reassert Polish independence.
the Polish state.

308
00:15:43.160 --> 00:15:44.760
They
wanted to prove to the world

309
00:15:44.920 --> 00:15:46.560
that they stood
on their own feet

310
00:15:46.720 --> 00:15:48.600
and that they fought to
liberate their own country.

311
00:15:48.760 --> 00:15:51.360
They don't want to give
up the Nazi dictatorship

312
00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:54.160
and just have it replaced
with a Soviet dictatorship.

313
00:15:56.640 --> 00:16:00.200
The Polish Home Army
and General Bór-Komorowski

314
00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:02.600
have long planned
for this moment.

315
00:16:04.520 --> 00:16:07.680
There are weapons caches.
command structures.

316
00:16:07.840 --> 00:16:09.960
There are instructions
coming from senior officers

317
00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:12.560
based in London.
There is a plan.

318
00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:16.800
Tens of thousands
of Home Army troops

319
00:16:16.960 --> 00:16:18.600
will go all over the city

320
00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:20.360
and go for the
most important things:

321
00:16:20.520 --> 00:16:21.880
the airports. the bridges.

322
00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:24.080
the main focal
points of Nazi power.

323
00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:28.680
It was a moment where
timing was everything.

324
00:16:28.840 --> 00:16:32.000
If they did it too soon.
the Germans would crush them.

325
00:16:32.160 --> 00:16:35.680
If they did it too late.
the Soviets would conquer them.

326
00:16:40.440 --> 00:16:41.720
The Red Army was coming.

327
00:16:41.880 --> 00:16:43.720
It looked as if there
was just this juggernaut

328
00:16:43.880 --> 00:16:46.200
that was gonna force
the Germans out of the city.

329
00:16:47.480 --> 00:16:50.320
Outside Warsaw.
the Germans regroup

330
00:16:50.480 --> 00:16:52.520
on the banks of the Vistula River.

331
00:16:53.600 --> 00:16:55.800
The Poles hear
the sounds of fighting.

332
00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:57.120
think the Red Army's gonna win.

333
00:16:57.280 --> 00:16:59.280
and they're about to
come into Warsaw.

334
00:17:00.360 --> 00:17:02.760
General Bór-Komorowski
gives the order

335
00:17:02.920 --> 00:17:04.880
to begin the uprising.

336
00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:19.360
The Poles have
been resisting the Germans

337
00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:21.040
for almost five years.

338
00:17:21.200 --> 00:17:24.160
Now. with the Soviets on
the other side of the Vistula.

339
00:17:24.320 --> 00:17:27.680
the Polish Home Army
seizes its opportunity.

340
00:17:27.840 --> 00:17:30.040
Because of the Red Army
coming so quickly

341
00:17:30.200 --> 00:17:31.680
up to the gates of Warsaw.

342
00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:35.320
General Bór-Komorowski gives
the order to start the uprising.

343
00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:37.840
The Polish Home Army
think this is the right moment.

344
00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.720
The Russians are approaching.
the Germans are clearly

345
00:17:40.880 --> 00:17:43.240
preparing to evacuate.
and the Poles

346
00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:46.400
appear out of the sewers.
out of the backstreets.

347
00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:49.960
out of the cellars. and
they raise the flag of rebellion.

348
00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:54.280
Civilians
are thrilled. they're jubilant.

349
00:17:54.440 --> 00:17:56.080
For the first time since 1939.

350
00:17:56.240 --> 00:17:57.680
they can sing
the national anthem.

351
00:17:57.840 --> 00:18:00.400
They push trams over.
they build barricades.

352
00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:02.240
and they make it very.
very difficult

353
00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:03.840
for the Germans to fight there.

354
00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:08.000
It's a heroic moment.
an exciting moment.

355
00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:11.600
Poland is rising like a phoenix
out of the ashes.

356
00:18:14.480 --> 00:18:17.120
But the attack does
not go as well as it was hoped.

357
00:18:17.280 --> 00:18:19.880
They do manage to
seize the Post Office.

358
00:18:20.040 --> 00:18:22.960
they manage to seize
an important German arsenal.

359
00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:25.040
but they don't manage
to secure the airportS.

360
00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:27.360
So it's up for grabs
by the end of that day.

361
00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:30.320
You get this sort of
twisted patchwork

362
00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:32.360
of Polish and German control.

363
00:18:32.520 --> 00:18:34.640
which ensures that
there is gonna be

364
00:18:34.800 --> 00:18:36.440
the mother of all street fights.

365
00:18:38.720 --> 00:18:40.880
The Polish Home Army
expected the Germans

366
00:18:41.040 --> 00:18:43.360
controlling Warsaw
to be in retreat.

367
00:18:47.120 --> 00:18:50.440
Instead. the Wehrmacht attacks
the Red Army at the Vistula...

368
00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:53.600
...and retains their
grip on Warsaw.

369
00:18:57.400 --> 00:18:59.640
Adolf Hitler meets
with Heinrich Himmler.

370
00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:02.200
head of the Nazi SS.

371
00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:05.720
On the night
of the 1st of August. 1944.

372
00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:07.520
Himmler goes up to
the Wolfsschanze.

373
00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:10.680
he sees Hitler.
and Hitler's raging around.

374
00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:13.280
And Himmler goes.
"You know. Mein Fuhrer.

375
00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:17.320
let's use this as a moment to
erase Warsaw from the map.

376
00:19:17.480 --> 00:19:19.920
Because this wretched city
has stood in our way

377
00:19:20.080 --> 00:19:22.200
of German expansion to
the East for hundreds of years.

378
00:19:22.360 --> 00:19:23.600
So let's just do it."

379
00:19:24.640 --> 00:19:27.800
So that evening. they give what's
called "the Order for Warsaw."

380
00:19:29.440 --> 00:19:31.080
The Germans have a plan to

381
00:19:31.240 --> 00:19:32.840
wipe Poland literally

382
00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.280
from the face of the Earth.

383
00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:37.480
One. you wanna send a message
to everybody else

384
00:19:37.640 --> 00:19:39.280
that this is
the cost of defying me.

385
00:19:39.440 --> 00:19:41.800
But the other reason is
you want to destroy Poland

386
00:19:41.960 --> 00:19:43.880
as a national identity.

387
00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:47.720
Every
combatant is to be killed.

388
00:19:47.880 --> 00:19:49.520
All men and women and children.

389
00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:50.920
civilians are to be killed.

390
00:19:51.080 --> 00:19:52.760
And then the city
is to be looted.

391
00:19:52.920 --> 00:19:55.760
and then "glattrasiert."
that means razed to the ground.

392
00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:03.040
The Germans
poured in ruthless shock troops

393
00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:05.120
with the express purpose
of destroying them.

394
00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:08.760
The Home Army used up
their caches of weapons very fast.

395
00:20:11.680 --> 00:20:13.960
The Poles
think the Red Army is coming.

396
00:20:14.120 --> 00:20:16.120
The whole thing
depended upon the idea

397
00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:17.760
that Germans were either leaving

398
00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:19.440
or could not reinforce

399
00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:21.400
their existing troops within Warsaw.

400
00:20:22.280 --> 00:20:24.840
Neither of those two things
turned out to be true.

401
00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:26.240
The Germans weren't leaving

402
00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:28.400
and the Soviets weren't coming.

403
00:20:28.560 --> 00:20:30.600
Stalin says.
to everyone's surprise:

404
00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:32.480
"Halt the army."

405
00:20:33.600 --> 00:20:37.320
They can see across the river:
Warsaw is burning.

406
00:20:39.080 --> 00:20:41.360
Although the Soviets
are right across the river.

407
00:20:41.520 --> 00:20:43.880
they make no effort to support

408
00:20:44.040 --> 00:20:46.760
the resistance in its uprising
against the Germans.

409
00:20:46.920 --> 00:20:48.440
Rather. they sit across the river

410
00:20:48.600 --> 00:20:50.920
and watch the Germans
crush the uprising.

411
00:20:52.320 --> 00:20:53.840
Stalin
doesn't just do nothing;

412
00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
he actively interferes
with the Allies' attempt

413
00:20:56.160 --> 00:20:58.280
to help the Home Army.
the Polish uprising.

414
00:20:59.640 --> 00:21:01.760
From their air bases in Italy.

415
00:21:01.920 --> 00:21:06.040
the British and Americans try
to drop supplies to the Poles.

416
00:21:06.200 --> 00:21:08.000
Churchill asks permission:

417
00:21:08.160 --> 00:21:11.080
"Can Allied planes carrying supplies
use Soviet bases

418
00:21:11.240 --> 00:21:13.320
to refuel and carry out repairs?"

419
00:21:13.480 --> 00:21:15.120
Stalin says no.

420
00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:17.280
Stalin has always hated

421
00:21:17.440 --> 00:21:19.280
the Polish government in London.

422
00:21:19.440 --> 00:21:22.160
which he regards as bourgeois.
imperialist. capitalist.

423
00:21:22.320 --> 00:21:26.280
He has a small
Polish communist group.

424
00:21:26.440 --> 00:21:28.760
He is always planning
to parachute them

425
00:21:28.920 --> 00:21:30.160
in to Poland as his government.

426
00:21:31.120 --> 00:21:34.000
And so Stalin is
content to watch the Germans

427
00:21:34.160 --> 00:21:36.000
utterly destroy
the Polish Home Army.

428
00:21:36.160 --> 00:21:38.000
destroy the population of Warsaw.

429
00:21:38.160 --> 00:21:40.000
and destroy the city itself.

430
00:21:40.160 --> 00:21:42.320
Stalin
wants to conquer Poland.

431
00:21:42.480 --> 00:21:43.840
but he wants to make sure

432
00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:47.520
that it's then turned into
a communist vassal client state.

433
00:21:47.680 --> 00:21:50.920
He wants to wait
until the Nazis have

434
00:21:51.080 --> 00:21:52.880
destroyed the Polish underground

435
00:21:53.040 --> 00:21:55.000
before he enters Warsaw.

436
00:21:55.160 --> 00:21:57.240
Let them do his work for him.

437
00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:04.360
Hitler sends in his
most psychopathic crews

438
00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:08.280
of murderous. grotesque sadists.

439
00:22:10.080 --> 00:22:12.480
Some of them
are the most brutal murderers

440
00:22:12.640 --> 00:22:13.960
of the entire Nazi regime.

441
00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:15.440
Like Oskar Dirlewanger.

442
00:22:15.600 --> 00:22:17.080
Even the SS doesn't
wanna work with him.

443
00:22:18.440 --> 00:22:20.600
They go through
building after building.

444
00:22:20.760 --> 00:22:22.800
and they round these
people up by the thousands

445
00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:24.600
and then mow those people down.

446
00:22:26.320 --> 00:22:28.600
When 5.000.
6.000 bodies are lying there.

447
00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:30.960
then they bring in the
Verbrennungskommando.

448
00:22:31.120 --> 00:22:33.240
these burning commandos.
to burn the bodies.

449
00:22:33.400 --> 00:22:34.960
specialists from places
like Treblinka

450
00:22:35.120 --> 00:22:38.440
who've now become specialists
at burning human flesh.

451
00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:44.760
They loot the entire city
and then they destroy it.

452
00:22:44.920 --> 00:22:47.280
Building by building.
libraries.

453
00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:49.320
museums. everything is destroyed.

454
00:22:53.120 --> 00:22:56.720
The Polish Home Army
surrenders.

455
00:22:56.880 --> 00:23:01.440
General Bór-Komorowski
is imprisoned by the Nazis.

456
00:23:03.080 --> 00:23:04.760
By the end of
the Warsaw Uprising.

457
00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:07.720
about 200.000
civilians have been killed.

458
00:23:09.120 --> 00:23:10.920
Then the remaining population

459
00:23:11.080 --> 00:23:13.000
are sent to camps like Auschwitz.

460
00:23:13.320 --> 00:23:15.960
Some are sent as slave laborers
into the Reich.

461
00:23:16.120 --> 00:23:17.920
So the destruction of Warsaw is

462
00:23:18.080 --> 00:23:19.760
unique in the destruction of cities

463
00:23:19.920 --> 00:23:21.200
in the Second World War in Europe.

464
00:23:22.320 --> 00:23:24.280
In Warsaw. tragically.

465
00:23:24.440 --> 00:23:27.320
the Germans chose
to meet that desire

466
00:23:27.480 --> 00:23:31.120
for Polish independence
with overwhelming force...

467
00:23:32.680 --> 00:23:36.400
...To kill and smash
and eradicate Polish culture.

468
00:23:39.040 --> 00:23:41.560
To say. "No.
you will not liberate yourselves.

469
00:23:41.720 --> 00:23:44.000
In fact.
you have condemned yourselves."

470
00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:52.680
August. 1944.

471
00:23:52.840 --> 00:23:56.160
The Germans are in
full retreat across France.

472
00:23:57.600 --> 00:23:59.720
They begin to evacuate Paris.

473
00:24:00.840 --> 00:24:04.280
Parisians sense a chance
to recapture their city.

474
00:24:05.440 --> 00:24:07.520
But they need a spark.

475
00:24:07.680 --> 00:24:09.880
On the 15th of August.
the Parisian police.

476
00:24:10.040 --> 00:24:12.320
which was 20.000 strong
and had been

477
00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:14.560
collaborating with the Germans
up to that moment.

478
00:24:14.720 --> 00:24:16.680
actually switches sides

479
00:24:16.840 --> 00:24:19.000
and raises the flag
on their building.

480
00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:22.800
giving the sign to
the rest of the city

481
00:24:22.960 --> 00:24:24.240
and. of course.
to the partisans.

482
00:24:24.400 --> 00:24:27.280
that this was the moment
the uprising needed to start.

483
00:24:30.800 --> 00:24:34.240
And so the streets of
Paris become a battlefield.

484
00:24:37.760 --> 00:24:40.680
The French resistance has
been preparing for this moment

485
00:24:40.840 --> 00:24:42.480
for a very long time.

486
00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:47.600
And they act against
the Germans quite rapidly

487
00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:49.080
and quite successfully.

488
00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:53.160
As this happened.

489
00:24:53.320 --> 00:24:55.320
Charles De Gaulle shows up
to Supreme Allied Commander

490
00:24:55.480 --> 00:24:56.720
Eisenhower's headquarters

491
00:24:56.880 --> 00:24:59.080
and go. "We have
to march on Paris."

492
00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:01.360
The Allies
don't particularly like De Gaulle.

493
00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:04.520
but see De Gaulle as a bulwark
against communism.

494
00:25:04.680 --> 00:25:06.120
Eisenhower
is smart enough to know

495
00:25:06.280 --> 00:25:07.800
that it would look really.
really good

496
00:25:07.960 --> 00:25:10.640
if the first troops to enter
Paris were the Free French.

497
00:25:12.120 --> 00:25:15.040
Eisenhower decides
to allow the Free French forces

498
00:25:15.200 --> 00:25:17.080
to send one division into the city

499
00:25:17.240 --> 00:25:20.480
and to help the insurgents
to free the city.

500
00:25:22.040 --> 00:25:24.280
Supported by the
American Fourth Division.

501
00:25:24.440 --> 00:25:26.840
General De Gaulle
orders the French

502
00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:29.080
Second Armored Division into Paris.

503
00:25:30.520 --> 00:25:32.040
Toward the bitter end.

504
00:25:32.200 --> 00:25:33.760
Adolf Hitler
issues instructions

505
00:25:33.920 --> 00:25:36.160
to General von Choltitz.
who was in control of Paris.

506
00:25:36.320 --> 00:25:37.640
to destroy the city.

507
00:25:37.800 --> 00:25:39.800
Hitler. during a phone
call with von Choltitz.

508
00:25:39.960 --> 00:25:41.520
asks: "Is Paris burning?"

509
00:25:42.760 --> 00:25:44.520
And von Choltitz tells him:

510
00:25:44.680 --> 00:25:46.360
"Yes. my Fuhrer.
we burned the city."

511
00:25:51.040 --> 00:25:54.360
Instead.
he negotiates a surrender.

512
00:26:03.240 --> 00:26:04.960
It is the officers
and men of that

513
00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:08.520
Second French Armored
Division who first enter Paris.

514
00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:16.280
So De Gaulle can claim
that the French have

515
00:26:16.440 --> 00:26:17.560
liberated their own capital.

516
00:26:17.720 --> 00:26:19.760
And not just any old French.
not the communist French.

517
00:26:19.920 --> 00:26:21.840
not the resis...
HIS French army.

518
00:26:27.720 --> 00:26:29.640
He is the one
leading the parade

519
00:26:29.800 --> 00:26:31.320
through the streets of Paris.

520
00:26:31.480 --> 00:26:34.360
presenting himself as the legitimate
leader of the French government.

521
00:26:39.600 --> 00:26:41.560
Everyone in
the city has come out now

522
00:26:41.720 --> 00:26:44.640
because they feel that their
moment of liberation is on them.

523
00:26:53.960 --> 00:26:57.280
But there are still
German soldiers in Paris.

524
00:27:07.880 --> 00:27:09.840
General De
Gaulle walked straight ahead

525
00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:11.920
into what appeared to me
to be a hail of fire.

526
00:27:12.080 --> 00:27:14.720
But he went straight ahead
without hesitation.

527
00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:16.640
his shoulders flung back.

528
00:27:20.200 --> 00:27:23.000
Most Germans
have surrendered or fled.

529
00:27:23.160 --> 00:27:25.240
The last are tracked down.

530
00:27:25.400 --> 00:27:27.400
along with French collaborators.

531
00:27:50.160 --> 00:27:52.200
He presents
the liberation of Paris

532
00:27:52.360 --> 00:27:54.320
as a story of self-liberation.

533
00:27:54.480 --> 00:27:56.440
a Paris that was
able to free itself

534
00:27:56.600 --> 00:27:59.000
from the yoke of
the German occupation

535
00:27:59.160 --> 00:28:00.520
without the help of the Allies.

536
00:28:07.040 --> 00:28:08.560
However. let's say.

537
00:28:08.720 --> 00:28:10.120
the Allied presence in the region

538
00:28:10.280 --> 00:28:11.640
also played a major role in

539
00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:14.000
convincing the Germans
that it was time to go.

540
00:28:15.680 --> 00:28:17.400
France will
enter this post-war period

541
00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:19.360
with pride and with confidence.

542
00:28:19.520 --> 00:28:21.560
It's difficult to imagine
how that would've happened

543
00:28:21.720 --> 00:28:24.240
if not for the efforts of all
of the resistance groups

544
00:28:24.400 --> 00:28:26.280
that fought against
Nazi aggression.

545
00:28:33.680 --> 00:28:36.000
But. in Warsaw.
the outcome is different.

546
00:28:36.960 --> 00:28:39.720
The city is razed by the Nazis.

547
00:28:41.160 --> 00:28:43.160
And what remains is captured

548
00:28:43.320 --> 00:28:45.000
and controlled by the Soviets.

549
00:28:48.960 --> 00:28:52.040
Paris. the city of light.
is saved.

550
00:28:53.240 --> 00:28:56.160
Warsaw. and the hope of
the Polish people.

551
00:28:56.320 --> 00:28:58.120
is destroyed.

552
00:29:16.200 --> 00:29:18.760
Resistance is important

553
00:29:18.920 --> 00:29:20.480
for the people of a nation

554
00:29:20.640 --> 00:29:23.120
who do not want
to be subjugated.

555
00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:26.560
While the French and the Poles

556
00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:28.360
rise up against the Germans

557
00:29:28.520 --> 00:29:32.040
within the extermination
camps at Auschwitz and others.

558
00:29:32.200 --> 00:29:35.360
there is also this
spirit of resistance.

559
00:29:40.080 --> 00:29:42.720
The deliberate
killing of Jews by the Nazis

560
00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:45.240
began with bullets.

561
00:29:47.160 --> 00:29:48.840
Shortly after the Germans

562
00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:51.920
invaded the Soviet Union
in June. 1941...

563
00:29:53.480 --> 00:29:56.800
...they started to shoot Jewish
children. women. and men...

564
00:29:57.800 --> 00:30:00.640
...and bury them in
ravines and forests.

565
00:30:03.560 --> 00:30:05.800
But eventually the Nazis
required

566
00:30:05.960 --> 00:30:09.360
a more systematic method
of murder.

567
00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:12.080
There were tens of
thousands of the camps

568
00:30:12.240 --> 00:30:14.200
by the end of the war.
It's a huge infrastructure.

569
00:30:14.360 --> 00:30:17.800
But there were a very
small number of death camps

570
00:30:17.960 --> 00:30:19.920
within this enormous system.

571
00:30:20.080 --> 00:30:22.200
Six death camps.

572
00:30:22.360 --> 00:30:24.040
Chelmno.
which is the original death camp.

573
00:30:24.200 --> 00:30:26.520
Belzec. Sobibor. Treblinka.

574
00:30:26.680 --> 00:30:28.120
and then Auschwitz-Birkenau

575
00:30:28.280 --> 00:30:29.720
and Majdanek.

576
00:30:31.520 --> 00:30:33.480
As the Red Army
pushes into Poland.

577
00:30:33.640 --> 00:30:36.680
the Nazis attempt to
hide their great crime

578
00:30:36.840 --> 00:30:39.520
by dismantling
the killing centers.

579
00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:43.960
They destroyed documents.

580
00:30:44.120 --> 00:30:45.720
They destroyed
the major death camps

581
00:30:45.880 --> 00:30:47.680
at Belzec. Sobibor.
and Treblinka.

582
00:30:47.840 --> 00:30:49.800
They get rid of the vast
majority of the buildings.

583
00:30:49.960 --> 00:30:51.320
They cover them over.

584
00:30:51.480 --> 00:30:52.800
They create farmhouses on the site

585
00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:54.480
to conceal everything
that they've done.

586
00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:56.840
And then as the camps
come into the path

587
00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:00.160
of invading Allied armies.
they evacuate them.

588
00:31:04.560 --> 00:31:06.560
At Auschwitz-Birkenau.
there are prisoners

589
00:31:06.720 --> 00:31:10.080
determined to
document the Nazi murders.

590
00:31:10.240 --> 00:31:12.320
The extermination
camp system

591
00:31:12.480 --> 00:31:14.640
includes the sorting of people.

592
00:31:14.800 --> 00:31:16.200
Some of them are left alive

593
00:31:16.360 --> 00:31:19.440
because they looked as if they
were young or fit or healthy enough.

594
00:31:19.600 --> 00:31:22.160
Those people work in something
called a Sonderkommando.

595
00:31:22.320 --> 00:31:25.480
They are supposed
to sort the clothing.

596
00:31:25.640 --> 00:31:27.800
sort the hair that's
been cut off people.

597
00:31:27.960 --> 00:31:30.360
to move the corpses.
all these terrible.

598
00:31:30.520 --> 00:31:32.200
terrible jobs
that they're given.

599
00:31:33.320 --> 00:31:35.200
In 1944 in
Auschwitz-Birkenau.

600
00:31:35.360 --> 00:31:36.800
members of the resistance movement

601
00:31:36.960 --> 00:31:39.040
manage to smuggle
a camera into the camp.

602
00:31:39.200 --> 00:31:41.520
The Sonderkommando.
who were witnessing

603
00:31:41.680 --> 00:31:43.200
all of these things
on a day-to-day basis.

604
00:31:43.360 --> 00:31:44.960
secure this camera.
and their ambition is to

605
00:31:45.120 --> 00:31:47.720
use this camera to
record images of

606
00:31:47.880 --> 00:31:49.600
what's happening within the camp

607
00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:52.920
in order for those pictures
to stir the world to respond.

608
00:31:54.040 --> 00:31:57.720
One prisoner
manages to photograph the horror.

609
00:32:05.640 --> 00:32:07.080
Four images of hell.

610
00:32:08.360 --> 00:32:10.800
The really
extraordinary thing about them

611
00:32:10.960 --> 00:32:12.960
is that the images
themselves are framed

612
00:32:13.120 --> 00:32:14.640
from within the doorway

613
00:32:14.800 --> 00:32:16.800
of the gas chamber building itself.

614
00:32:16.960 --> 00:32:20.080
So the images testify
to the bravery

615
00:32:20.240 --> 00:32:22.120
of what this man was doing

616
00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:24.560
and the appalling depravity

617
00:32:24.720 --> 00:32:26.920
of the process at that stage.

618
00:32:27.960 --> 00:32:29.840
And what we see
within these images

619
00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:33.480
are the burning of bodies
outside the crematoria.

620
00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:37.120
And we see people being undressed.

621
00:32:37.280 --> 00:32:39.160
waiting to be brought
into the gas chamber.

622
00:32:42.800 --> 00:32:45.320
The film is
put into a tube of toothpaste

623
00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:48.200
and then smuggled out
to the Polish Home Army.

624
00:32:49.640 --> 00:32:53.160
This is perhaps
the single most valuable

625
00:32:53.320 --> 00:32:56.120
photographic evidence
to emerge from Auschwitz.

626
00:32:59.560 --> 00:33:02.280
The Jews fought back from 1933

627
00:33:02.440 --> 00:33:03.680
to the end of the war.

628
00:33:03.840 --> 00:33:05.120
There are escapes.

629
00:33:05.280 --> 00:33:08.880
There are individual killings
of guards by prisoners.

630
00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:11.960
The Jews are fighting
back this entire time.

631
00:33:12.960 --> 00:33:15.560
Resistance is what
gives us testimony

632
00:33:15.720 --> 00:33:17.200
of what happened
in those places.

633
00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:23.520
In the fall of 1944.

634
00:33:23.680 --> 00:33:26.400
Nazi Germany is retreating
on all fronts...

635
00:33:26.560 --> 00:33:27.840
except one:

636
00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.200
their war against the Jews.

637
00:33:31.480 --> 00:33:35.080
Auschwitz-Birkenau
is now the front line.

638
00:33:38.160 --> 00:33:40.760
Killing Jews is not
a secondary by-product

639
00:33:40.920 --> 00:33:43.760
of their military goals:
It is their military goal.

640
00:33:46.120 --> 00:33:47.960
From Hitler's
perspective. it's worth

641
00:33:48.120 --> 00:33:49.760
apportioning resources to it

642
00:33:49.920 --> 00:33:52.080
despite what's
happening elsewhere.

643
00:33:52.240 --> 00:33:55.920
In fact. they accelerate
the process of mass murder.

644
00:33:57.440 --> 00:34:00.640
In 1944.
the Nazis decide to

645
00:34:00.800 --> 00:34:03.400
exterminate the Hungarian
Jewish population.

646
00:34:03.560 --> 00:34:06.440
So a special train line is
built into Auschwitz-Birkenau.

647
00:34:06.600 --> 00:34:08.360
and hundreds of thousands of

648
00:34:08.520 --> 00:34:10.240
Hungarian Jews are rounded up.

649
00:34:10.400 --> 00:34:11.760
and many of them are murdered

650
00:34:11.920 --> 00:34:14.680
within a few hours of
their arriving at the camp.

651
00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:19.720
1944 is
when Auschwitz hits

652
00:34:19.880 --> 00:34:22.640
its terrible. appalling peak

653
00:34:22.800 --> 00:34:25.520
in terms of the number
of people killed.

654
00:34:30.080 --> 00:34:32.720
Requests start to
come to the U.S. government

655
00:34:32.880 --> 00:34:35.360
to bomb either the rail lines.

656
00:34:35.520 --> 00:34:38.080
the gas chambers at Auschwitz.
the crematoria.

657
00:34:38.240 --> 00:34:41.320
the bridges leading
to these camps.

658
00:34:42.800 --> 00:34:44.960
The idea of
bombing death camps

659
00:34:45.120 --> 00:34:47.760
is difficult operationally
and it's difficult morally.

660
00:34:47.920 --> 00:34:49.400
You're going to kill the very people

661
00:34:49.560 --> 00:34:51.000
that you're trying to rescue.

662
00:34:53.080 --> 00:34:55.400
Churchill and
Roosevelt's perspective:

663
00:34:55.560 --> 00:34:57.920
humanitarian concerns
were always secondary

664
00:34:58.080 --> 00:34:59.760
to winning the war.
They would say:

665
00:34:59.920 --> 00:35:02.320
"The best thing that we
can do to help these people

666
00:35:02.480 --> 00:35:05.840
is to bring the war to an
end as quickly as possible."

667
00:35:07.680 --> 00:35:10.160
Prisoners at
Auschwitz-Birkenau cannot

668
00:35:10.320 --> 00:35:12.080
afford to wait for the war to end.

669
00:35:12.240 --> 00:35:15.680
They want to survive.
they want to escape.

670
00:35:15.840 --> 00:35:19.120
and they want to
stop the killing.

671
00:35:24.640 --> 00:35:26.440
From the beginning.
there has been

672
00:35:26.600 --> 00:35:29.560
an underground of resistance
at Auschwitz-Birkenau

673
00:35:29.720 --> 00:35:32.240
made up of various
groups of prisoners.

674
00:35:32.400 --> 00:35:34.080
including the Sonderkommando.

675
00:35:35.360 --> 00:35:37.480
The Sonderkommando
starts to realize that

676
00:35:37.640 --> 00:35:39.440
there are fewer and fewer
of these transports

677
00:35:39.600 --> 00:35:40.960
coming from Hungary.

678
00:35:41.120 --> 00:35:44.920
"The extermination process is
finishing; our time is coming.

679
00:35:45.080 --> 00:35:47.240
and if we don't act quickly.
we're going to be killed."

680
00:35:48.600 --> 00:35:51.360
So they started to
look at ways they could resist.

681
00:35:51.520 --> 00:35:53.200
They might die trying.

682
00:35:53.360 --> 00:35:54.480
there's a very good chance

683
00:35:54.640 --> 00:35:55.720
that they'll die trying. but

684
00:35:55.880 --> 00:35:57.760
at least they can
give themselves a chance.

685
00:35:57.920 --> 00:36:00.480
Because they're determined
to do whatever they can

686
00:36:00.640 --> 00:36:03.120
to meet the moment
on their own terms.

687
00:36:04.400 --> 00:36:06.280
Auschwitz is
a death camp.

688
00:36:06.440 --> 00:36:09.360
and it's also a forced
labor facility.

689
00:36:09.520 --> 00:36:11.600
And so there were women

690
00:36:11.760 --> 00:36:13.200
who were working in the armaments

691
00:36:13.360 --> 00:36:14.600
factories nearby Auschwitz

692
00:36:14.760 --> 00:36:17.320
who had access to gunpowder.

693
00:36:18.760 --> 00:36:20.000
One member
of the underground

694
00:36:20.160 --> 00:36:22.840
is part of a slave labor unit
that sorts the clothing

695
00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:25.280
of the dead: Roza Robota.

696
00:36:25.440 --> 00:36:27.440
She makes contact
with the Sonderkommando.

697
00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:30.320
They form a plan to
destroy the crematoria.

698
00:36:30.480 --> 00:36:32.800
provoke a wider uprising.

699
00:36:32.960 --> 00:36:34.480
and attempt to escape.

700
00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:38.040
Robota enlists Jewish women

701
00:36:38.200 --> 00:36:41.160
working in the munitions factory
to smuggle gunpowder:

702
00:36:42.040 --> 00:36:43.240
Ala Gertner.

703
00:36:43.400 --> 00:36:45.040
Regina Safirsztajn.

704
00:36:45.200 --> 00:36:46.560
and Esther Wajcblum.

705
00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:49.520
So they secured these
explosives at enormous risk.

706
00:36:49.680 --> 00:36:50.960
and they're smuggling
them through

707
00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:53.920
various kind of ingenious means.
They create little packets of

708
00:36:54.080 --> 00:36:56.840
fabric that they hide them in.
and they get them through.

709
00:36:58.320 --> 00:37:00.120
The women
are collecting the gunpowder

710
00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:02.120
to hand them off
to their friend Roza.

711
00:37:02.280 --> 00:37:03.760
She is going to
get the gunpowder

712
00:37:03.920 --> 00:37:05.560
into the hands of the
Sonderkommando.

713
00:37:05.720 --> 00:37:07.640
who are going to
use it to try to blow up

714
00:37:07.800 --> 00:37:09.240
the crematoria
where they're working.

715
00:37:11.920 --> 00:37:14.520
At a certain moment.
an individual takes

716
00:37:14.680 --> 00:37:17.320
an improvised weapon and
launches at a member of the SS.

717
00:37:17.480 --> 00:37:19.400
and that kick-starts
the whole thing.

718
00:37:22.040 --> 00:37:24.480
There's smoke.
there's noise. there's shouting.

719
00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:26.120
and there's gunfire.

720
00:37:29.120 --> 00:37:32.640
The resistors
end up blowing up. in part.

721
00:37:32.800 --> 00:37:35.080
one of the crematoria.
Crematoria IV.

722
00:37:36.480 --> 00:37:38.360
It's put permanently
out of commission.

723
00:37:38.520 --> 00:37:40.120
So the Sonderkommando
would've considered

724
00:37:40.280 --> 00:37:41.560
that to be a success.

725
00:37:42.640 --> 00:37:44.840
And in another crematory building.
the Sonderkommando

726
00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:48.720
force some the guards
into one of the ovens alive.

727
00:37:52.240 --> 00:37:54.200
Some prisoners escape.

728
00:37:54.360 --> 00:37:56.520
but are quickly
caught and executed.

729
00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:01.640
The three
women who have been

730
00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:03.320
stealing the gunpowder.

731
00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:06.200
plus Roza Robota
are to be hanged..

732
00:38:07.120 --> 00:38:09.360
And just as the noose
is put around her neck.

733
00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:13.800
she yells out to the group
of prisoners assembled:

734
00:38:15.280 --> 00:38:18.360
"Vengeance."
or. "Sisters. avenge."

735
00:38:19.680 --> 00:38:23.080
It is a passionate message
of resilience. resistance.

736
00:38:23.240 --> 00:38:25.080
and continue the fight.

737
00:38:28.080 --> 00:38:30.400
In December.
the Red Army advances

738
00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:32.360
on Auschwitz-Birkenau.

739
00:38:35.720 --> 00:38:39.560
The SS forced prisoners
on marches into Germany.

740
00:38:42.120 --> 00:38:44.280
Thousands die.

741
00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:50.840
On January 27th. 1945.

742
00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:55.480
Soviet soldiers arrive at the
gates of Auschwitz-Birkenau.

743
00:38:57.360 --> 00:39:00.400
Auschwitz
really became the center

744
00:39:00.560 --> 00:39:03.480
of the mass murder of Europe's
Jews quite late in the war.

745
00:39:03.640 --> 00:39:07.160
The important thing to
know is that 80%

746
00:39:07.320 --> 00:39:08.640
of the Jews murdered
in the Holocaust

747
00:39:08.800 --> 00:39:10.320
were not murdered at Auschwitz.

748
00:39:10.480 --> 00:39:12.360
but elsewhere in places
that are either

749
00:39:12.520 --> 00:39:14.600
forgotten or largely overlooked.

750
00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:21.560
The Nazis
and their collaborators

751
00:39:21.720 --> 00:39:24.240
murder six million Jews
during the war.

752
00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:28.840
Millions of others
die at their hands.

753
00:39:31.240 --> 00:39:33.800
But in the face of
unimaginable conditions

754
00:39:33.960 --> 00:39:36.280
and inconceivable cruelty...

755
00:39:39.240 --> 00:39:42.120
...some find a way to resist.

756
00:39:43.240 --> 00:39:45.440
Resistance
takes so many forms.

757
00:39:45.600 --> 00:39:47.800
There's armed
resistance and uprising.

758
00:39:47.960 --> 00:39:50.280
and that happens
throughout Europe.

759
00:39:50.440 --> 00:39:52.560
There is spiritual resistance.

760
00:39:52.720 --> 00:39:55.080
Just the idea that
you are not going to die

761
00:39:55.240 --> 00:39:56.680
just because
the Nazis want you to.

762
00:39:56.840 --> 00:39:58.040
you are going to try to survive.

763
00:39:58.200 --> 00:39:59.880
You are going to document

764
00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:02.240
what is happening.
write letters. write diaries.

765
00:40:02.400 --> 00:40:03.920
bury them in the ground

766
00:40:04.080 --> 00:40:06.320
so that someday we will be able to

767
00:40:06.480 --> 00:40:08.120
talk about what
you went through.

768
00:40:10.840 --> 00:40:13.880
The nature of tyranny
becomes evident in World War II.

769
00:40:14.040 --> 00:40:15.320
The Nazis and the Japanese

770
00:40:15.480 --> 00:40:18.000
imperialists
are invading their neighbors.

771
00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:19.840
kidnapping. slave laborers.

772
00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:21.840
murdering those
who disagree with them.

773
00:40:22.840 --> 00:40:24.400
It was a natural reaction

774
00:40:24.560 --> 00:40:26.400
on the part of
the occupied peoples

775
00:40:26.560 --> 00:40:29.080
to organize some
form of resistance.

776
00:40:29.240 --> 00:40:32.000
And it happens
all over the world in World War II.

777
00:40:35.360 --> 00:40:38.080
After surviving
Auschwitz and Buchenwald.

778
00:40:38.240 --> 00:40:40.880
Nobel Laureate Elie Wiesel said:

779
00:40:41.040 --> 00:40:43.320
"We must always take sides.

780
00:40:43.480 --> 00:40:46.520
Neutrality helps the oppressor.
never the victim.

781
00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:49.080
Silence encourages the tormentor.

782
00:40:49.240 --> 00:40:50.960
never the tormented.

783
00:40:51.120 --> 00:40:53.800
Sometimes we must interfere."

784
00:40:54.720 --> 00:40:57.960
In the Pacific. President
Franklin Roosevelt.

785
00:40:58.120 --> 00:41:00.760
General Douglas MacArthur.
and Admiral Chester Nimitz

786
00:41:00.920 --> 00:41:04.440
meet in Pearl Harbor to draw
a plan for the final defeat

787
00:41:04.600 --> 00:41:07.126
- of Imperial Japan.
